    "history":  {
                    "es":  "Maria Auxiliadora �cuyo titulo latino es Auxilium Christianorum, Auxilio de los Cristianos� es una de las advocaciones marianas de mayor expansion en la historia moderna, estrechamente ligada a la figura de San Juan Bosco y a la Congregacion Salesiana. La imagen venerada en Turin no es una aparicion sino un encargo: Don Bosco mando pintar al artista Carlo Thomatis en 1865-1868 una imagen de Maria segun la descripcion que el mismo habia recibido en suenos, y la imagen quedo terminada justo cuando la basilica construida por voto de Don Bosco estaba lista para ser consagrada.\n\nEl origen del titulo �Auxilio de los Cristianos� es mucho mas antiguo: el Papa Pio V lo introdujo en las Letanias Lauretanas tras la victoria de la batalla de Lepanto el 7 de octubre de 1571, en la que la flota cristiana derroto al Imperio Otomano. Pio V, que habia convocado a toda la cristiandad a rezar el Rosario durante la batalla, atribuyo la victoria a la intercesion de Maria, Auxilium Christianorum. El Papa Pio VII, liberado en 1814 tras cinco anos de cautiverio napoleonico, atribuyo su liberacion a la misma intercesion y fijo el 24 de mayo como fiesta de Maria Auxiliadora en toda la Iglesia.\n\nDon Bosco (1815-1888), huerfano de padre a los dos anos, fundador de la Congregacion Salesiana y padre espiritual de miles de jovenes marginados en Turin, fue el gran propagador de esta devocion. Desde los cuatro anos tuvo el primer sueno profetico en que veia a Maria como su guia; desde entonces su vida fue una serie de suenos simbolicos que el interpretaba como mensajes divinos. Construyo la basilica de Valdocco entre 1863 y 1868 cumpliendo el voto que habia hecho durante la epidemia de colera de 1854, y desde su inauguracion el 9 de junio de 1868 el santuario se convirtio en el corazon espiritual del mundo salesiano.\n\nHoy la Congregacion Salesiana �con mas de 15.000 sacerdotes y hermanos presentes en 134 paises� mantiene la devocion a Maria Auxiliadora como pilar de su espiritualidad. Los Salesianos de Don Bosco y las Hijas de Maria Auxiliadora (FMA), fundadas por Don Bosco y Santa Maria Dominica Mazzarello, forman juntos una de las familias religiosas mas grandes del mundo, todas bajo la proteccion de quien Don Bosco llamo simplemente �mi Madre�.\n\n1. EL SUE�O DE LAS DOS COLUMNAS: EL MAPA DEL FUTURO DE LA IGLESIA (1862)\nUna noche de 1862, Don Bosco tuvo uno de los sue�os prof�ticos m�s impresionantes de la historia moderna. Vio una flota de barcos enemigos atacando a la nave de la Iglesia, pilotada por el Papa. Entre las olas y el fuego, el Papa guiaba la nave hacia dos enormes columnas en medio del mar: en la primera ardia el Sant�simo Sacramento; en la segunda, una imagen de Mar�a Auxiliadora con la inscripci�n �Auxilium christianorum�. Cuando el Papa logr� atar la nave a las dos columnas, la tormenta ces� y los barcos enemigos naufragaron. Don Bosco declar� que este sue�o era un mapa del futuro de la Iglesia y que la salvaci�n pasar�a por la Eucarist�a y por Mar�a Auxiliadora. La visi�n se difundi� por toda Europa y precipit� la devoci�n moderna a Mar�a bajo este t�tulo.\n\n2. LA PLAGA DE C�LERA EN TUR�N Y LOS CIEN D�AS SIN UNA MUERTE (1854)\nEn el oto�o de 1854, el c�lera arras� Tur�n matando miles de personas. Don Bosco envi� a sus muchachos a cuidar a los col�ricos por toda la ciudad �tarea que aterraba a m�dicos y adultos�. Antes de enviarlos, hizo una promesa p�blica a Mar�a Auxiliadora: si ninguno de sus muchachos mor�a durante la epidemia, construir�a una bas�lica en su honor. Durante m�s de cien d�as de servicio en los barrios m�s golpeados de Tur�n, cientos de j�venes salesianos atendieron enfermos sin un solo contagio mortal. Al final de la epidemia, Don Bosco cumpli� su voto: el 9 de junio de 1868 fue inaugurada la Bas�lica de Mar�a Auxiliadora en el barrio Valdocco de Tur�n, que hoy es el coraz�n espiritual de la Congregaci�n Salesiana en el mundo.\n\n3. LA CURACI�N DE CATERINA FILIPPI Y EL PRIMER MILAGRO OFICIAL (1864)\nEl primer milagro can�nico atribuido a Mar�a Auxiliadora bajo el t�tulo formal fue la curaci�n de Caterina Filippi, una joven de Mornese �la misma aldea donde m�s tarde nacer�a la Congregaci�n de las Hijas de Mar�a Auxiliadora, fundada por Don Bosco y Santa Mar�a Dominica Mazzarello�. Caterina sufr�a una enfermedad pulmonar incurable que la dejaba sin fuerzas para moverse. El m�dico hab�a certificado que morir�a antes de fin de a�o. La joven comenz� una novena a Mar�a Auxiliadora con absoluta confianza. Al s�ptimo d�a de la novena, se levant� de la cama completamente sana, sin ning�n s�ntoma. El m�dico, at�nito, no encontr� explicaci�n. Caterina vivi� muchos a�os m�s, y su curaci�n fue documentada y enviada a Roma como parte del proceso que llevar�a a la proclamaci�n formal de la fiesta de Mar�a Auxiliadora el 24 de mayo de 1868 por el Papa P�o IX.",
                    "en":  "Mary Help of Christians � whose Latin title is Auxilium Christianorum � is one of the Marian devotions with the greatest expansion in modern history, closely linked to Saint John Bosco and the Salesian Congregation. The image venerated in Turin is not an apparition but a commission: Don Bosco asked artist Carlo Thomatis in 1865-1868 to paint an image of Mary according to the description he himself had received in dreams, and the image was completed just as the basilica built by Don Bosco\u0027s vow was ready to be consecrated.\n\nThe origin of the title \u0027Help of Christians\u0027 is much older: Pope Pius V introduced it into the Lauretan Litany after the victory at the Battle of Lepanto on October 7, 1571, in which the Christian fleet defeated the Ottoman Empire. Pius V, who had called all Christendom to pray the Rosary during the battle, attributed the victory to the intercession of Mary, Auxilium Christianorum. Pope Pius VII, freed in 1814 after five years of Napoleonic captivity, attributed his liberation to the same intercession and fixed May 24 as the feast of Mary Help of Christians throughout the Church.\n\nDon Bosco (1815-1888), orphaned of his father at age two, founder of the Salesian Congregation and spiritual father to thousands of marginalized youth in Turin, was the great propagator of this devotion. From the age of four he had his first prophetic dream in which he saw Mary as his guide; from then on his life was a series of symbolic dreams he interpreted as divine messages. He built the Valdocco basilica between 1863 and 1868, fulfilling the vow he had made during the cholera epidemic of 1854, and from its inauguration on June 9, 1868, the shrine became the spiritual heart of the Salesian world.\n\nToday the Salesian Congregation � with more than 15,000 priests and brothers present in 134 countries � maintains devotion to Mary Help of Christians as a pillar of its spirituality. The Salesians of Don Bosco and the Daughters of Mary Help of Christians (FMA), founded by Don Bosco and Saint Mary Dominica Mazzarello, together form one of the largest religious families in the world, all under the protection of the one Don Bosco simply called \u0027my Mother.\u0027\n\n1. THE DREAM OF THE TWO PILLARS: A MAP OF THE CHURCH\u0027S FUTURE (1862)\nOne night in 1862, Don Bosco had one of the most impressive prophetic dreams of modern history. He saw a fleet of enemy ships attacking the vessel of the Church, piloted by the Pope. Amid the waves and fire, the Pope guided the ship toward two enormous columns in the middle of the sea: on the first burned the Blessed Sacrament; on the second, an image of Mary Help of Christians with the inscription \u0027Auxilium christianorum.\u0027 When the Pope managed to tie the ship to the two columns, the storm ceased and the enemy ships sank. Don Bosco declared that this dream was a map of the Church\u0027s future and that salvation would come through the Eucharist and through Mary Help of Christians. The vision spread throughout Europe and precipitated the modern devotion to Mary under this title.\n\n2. THE CHOLERA PLAGUE IN TURIN AND ONE HUNDRED DAYS WITHOUT A DEATH (1854)\nIn the autumn of 1854, cholera swept through Turin, killing thousands. Don Bosco sent his boys to care for cholera victims throughout the city � a task that terrified doctors and adults. Before sending them, he made a public promise to Mary Help of Christians: if none of his boys died during the epidemic, he would build a basilica in her honor. For more than one hundred days of service in the hardest-hit neighborhoods of Turin, hundreds of Salesian young men tended the sick without a single fatal contagion. At the end of the epidemic, Don Bosco fulfilled his vow: on June 9, 1868, the Basilica of Mary Help of Christians was inaugurated in the Valdocco neighborhood of Turin � today the spiritual heart of the Salesian Congregation worldwide.\n\n3. THE HEALING OF CATERINA FILIPPI AND THE FIRST OFFICIAL MIRACLE (1864)\nThe first canonical miracle attributed to Mary Help of Christians under the formal title was the healing of Caterina Filippi, a young woman from Mornese � the very village where the Congregation of the Daughters of Mary Help of Christians would later be born, founded by Don Bosco and Saint Mary Dominica Mazzarello. Caterina suffered from an incurable pulmonary disease that left her without the strength to move. The doctor had certified that she would die before year\u0027s end. The young woman began a novena to Mary Help of Christians with absolute trust. On the seventh day of the novena, she rose from her bed completely well, with no symptoms whatsoever. The astonished doctor found no explanation. Caterina lived many more years, and her healing was documented and sent to Rome as part of the process that would lead to the formal proclamation of the feast of Mary Help of Christians on May 24, 1868 by Pope Pius IX."
